 The more general statement that 
\begin_inset Formula $a+b=b+a$
\end_inset

 for any numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is called the commutative property for addition of real numbers.
 Though this property is one of the basic principles that can be proven
 based on even more basic principles, we will take the viewpoint that it
 had to turn out this way! The counting numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,3,\ldots$
\end_inset

, represent how many of a thing we have (quantity).
 This is a fact engrained in our minds as we learn to count—at a very young
 age.
 Addition models what happens when two quantities are merged—another concept
 engrained in our minds early on in our mental development.
 If you add three apples to a basket initially holding one apple, afterward
 it will contain four apples.
 This merger is modeled by the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $1+3=4$
\end_inset

 (one apple plus three more apples gives you four apples).
 Similarly if you add one apple to a basket initially holding three apples,
 afterward it will contain four apples.
 This merger is modeled by the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $3+1=4$
\end_inset

.
 The fact that a pair of natural numbers can be added in either order with
 the same result is simply the way natural numbers work.
 Any mathematical axiom, theorem, or proof suggesting otherwise is simply
 not the number system we were taught as youngsters.
