\begin_layout Standard
Claim 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:commutativityforaddition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be proven by noting that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A+B)_{i:j}=A_{i:j}+B_{i:j}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(B+A)_{i:j}=B_{i:j}+A_{i:j}
\]

\end_inset

by definition of matrix addition.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i:j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{i:j}$
\end_inset

 are numbers, the commutative property for addition of real numbers allows
 us to use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i:j}+B_{i:j}=B_{i:j}+A_{i:j}$
\end_inset

 to deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A+B)_{i:j}=(B+A)_{i:j}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B+A$
\end_inset

 are equal, the matrices are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In more words than symbols, the argument goes thus.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 plus the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B+A$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 plus the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 But since the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are numbers, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 plus the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the same as the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 plus the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

 is the same as the 
\begin_inset Formula $i,\!j$
\end_inset

-entry of 
\begin_inset Formula $B+A$
\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B=B+A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

